  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "There are several standard-ish and not-yet-conventional node labels used to indicate node location, failure domain, and so forth that we should pass through to Ceph so that the CRUSH hierarchy is built properly.\r\n\r\nThese labels include, on AWS,\r\n\r\n- failure-domain.beta.kubernetes.io/region\r\n- failure-domain.beta.kubernetes.io/zone\r\n\r\nFor bare metal, we might create our own convention, if there is not yet one under kubernetes.io:\r\n\r\n- rook.io/rack\r\n- rook.io/room\r\n- rook.io/datacenter\r\n\r\n(Alternatively/eventually, we can extend teh kubernetes.io namespace; see https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubernetes-api/labels-annotations-taints/)\r\n\r\nThe goal is that when the OSD pod and OSD are created, the OSD is placed correctly in the CRUSH hierarchy based on these labels.  From Ceph's perspective, this is normally done with a configuration variable like ``crush_location = rack=foo host=bar`` or ``crush_location = region=us-east-1 zone=whatever host=foo``.  That value needs to be present for the OSD the first time it starts up, presumably either via the command line (``--crush-location=rack=foo,row=bar``) or the ``CEPH_ARGS`` environment variable containing the same.",
